The paper deals with finding dense substructures in a graph, which is a fundamental problem in graph mining. This problem has applications in various fields such as bioinformatics, social networks, and visualization. The paper proposes a new approach called nucleus decomposition, which represents the graph as a forest of nuclei and provides a hierarchy of dense subgraphs. This approach is evaluated on real graphs and is shown to be more efficient and effective than other state-of-the-art solutions. Given the focus on graph mining and analysis, the most likely sub-category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Other likely sub-categories include cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), cs.SOC (Social and Information Networks), cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition), and cs.DB (Databases).
